17","Abt 1040":"about 1040","0982":"0982","1069":"1069","0990":"0990","1012":"1012","1011":"1011","1075":"1075","1020":"1020","1040":"1040","Germany":"Germany","Querfurt, Sachsen, Bavaria, Germany":"Querfurt, Saxony, Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"VON","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Vaughan  .","Chinese: variant of   Wong  .","Cambodian: written វ៉ុន, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Ida","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Norman name, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>īd</i> ‘work’. This died out during the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, influenced by its use in  Tennyson's  The Princess (  1847 ) for the central character, who devotes herself to the cause of women's rights and women's education in a thoroughly Victorian way. The name is also associated with Mount Ida in Crete, which was connected in classical times with the worship of Zeus, king of the gods, who was supposed to have been brought up in a cave on the mountainside. In the 1930s it became famous as the name of the film star  Ida Lupino  (  1914–1995 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ida VON QUERFURT was born in 1012, in Querfurt, Saxony, Germany, her father, Gebhard von Querfurt I, was 30 and her mother, Ida von Goseck, was 23. She married Bernhard VON SUPPLINBURG in 1039. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1012–":"1012–Surnud","1012–Female":"1012–Surnud","1020–1040":"1020–1040","1011–1069":"1011–1069","1040–1075":"1040–1075","0982–1017":"0982–1017","0990–Female":"0990–Surnud","1039":